# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nebula-graph
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph is an open-source, distributed, easily scalable, and native graph database.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] It is capable of hosting graphs with hundreds of billions of vertices and trillions of edges, and serving queries with millisecond-latency.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] A graph database, such as NebulaGraph, is a database that specializes in storing vast graph networks and retrieving information from them.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] It efficiently stores data as vertices (nodes) and edges (relationships) in labeled property graphs.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Properties can be attached to both vertices and edges.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Each vertex can have one or multiple tags (labels).
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Graph databases are well suited for storing most kinds of data models abstracted from reality.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Things are connected in almost all fields in the world.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Modeling systems like relational databases extract the relationships between entities and squeeze them into table columns alone, with their types and properties stored in other columns or even other tables.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] This makes data management time-consuming and cost-ineffective.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph, as a typical native graph database, allows you to store the rich relationships as edges with edge types and properties directly attached to them.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph is open under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] More and more people such as database developers, data scientists, security experts, and algorithm engineers are participating in the designing and development of NebulaGraph.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] To join the opening of source code and ideas, surf the NebulaGraph GitHub page.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Written in C++ and born for graphs, NebulaGraph handles graph queries in milliseconds.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Among most databases, NebulaGraph shows superior performance in providing graph data services.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] The larger the data size, the greater the superiority of NebulaGraph.For more information, see NebulaGraph benchmarking.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph is designed in a shared-nothing architecture and supports scaling in and out without interrupting the database service.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph supports clients in popular programming languages like Java, Python, C++, and Go, and more are under development.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] For more information, see NebulaGraph clients.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph supports strict role-based access control and external authentication servers such as LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) servers to enhance data security.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] For more information, see Authentication and authorization.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] More and more native tools of NebulaGraph have been released, such as NebulaGraph Studio, NebulaGraph Console, and NebulaGraph Exchange.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] For more ecosystem tools, see Ecosystem tools overview.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Besides, NebulaGraph has the ability to be integrated with many cutting-edge technologies, such as Spark, Flink, and HBase, for the purpose of mutual strengthening in a world of increasing challenges and chances.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] The native NebulaGraph Query Language, also known as nGQL, is a declarative, openCypher-compatible textual query language.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] It is easy to understand and easy to use.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Solid-state drives have extremely high performance and they are getting cheaper.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Compared with products based on HDD and large memory, it is more suitable for future hardware trends and easier to achieve balanced reading and writing.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] You can easily model the connected data into NebulaGraph for your business without forcing them into a structure such as a relational table, and properties can be added, updated, and deleted freely.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] For more information, see Data modeling.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph is being used by tech leaders such as Tencent, Vivo, Meituan, and JD Digits.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] For more information, visit the NebulaGraph official website.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph can be used to support various graph-based scenarios.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] To spare the time spent on pushing the kinds of data mentioned in this section into relational databases and on bothering with join queries, use NebulaGraph.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Financial institutions have to traverse countless transactions to piece together potential crimes and understand how combinations of transactions and devices might be related to a single fraud scheme.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] This kind of scenario can be modeled in graphs, and with the help of NebulaGraph, fraud rings and other sophisticated scams can be easily detected.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph offers the ability to instantly process the real-time information produced by a visitor and make accurate recommendations on articles, videos, products, and services.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Natural languages can be transformed into knowledge graphs and stored in NebulaGraph.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] A question organized in a natural language can be resolved by a semantic parser in an intelligent question-answer system and re-organized.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Then, possible answers to the question can be retrieved from the knowledge graph and provided to the one who asked the question.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] Information on people and their relationships is typical graph data.
[src:nebula-graph/1-what-is-nebula-graph] NebulaGraph can easily handle the social networking information of billions of people and trillions of relationships, and provide lightning-fast queries for friend recommendations and job promotions in the case of massive concurrency.
[src:nebula-graph/blob-readme-md] The following figure shows the architecture of the **NebulaGraph** core.
[src:nebula-graph/blob-readme-md] Read the getting started docs for a quick start.
[src:nebula-graph/blob-readme-md] NebulaGraph is a distributed graph database with multiple components.
[src:nebula-graph/blob-readme-md] NebulaGraph comes with a set of tools to help you manage and monitor your graph database.
[src:nebula-graph/blob-readme-md] Contributions are warmly welcomed and greatly appreciated.
[src:nebula-graph/blob-readme-md] NebulaGraph enriches the CNCF Database Landscape.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:nebula-graph/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **graph** is an abstract data type that is meant to implement the undirected graph and directed graph concepts from the field of graph theory within mathematics.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure consists of a finite (and possibly mutable) set of *vertices* (also called *nodes* or *points*), together with a set of unordered pairs of these vertices for an undirected graph or a set of ordered pairs for a directed graph.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] These pairs are known as *edges* (also called *links* or *lines*), and for a directed graph are also known as *edges* but also sometimes *arrows* or *arcs*.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertices may be part of the graph structure, or may be external entities represented by integer indices or references.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure may also associate to each edge some *edge value*, such as a symbolic label or a numeric attribute (cost, capacity, length, etc.).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] This data structure allows the storage of additional data on the vertices.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Additional data can be stored if edges are also stored as objects, in which case each vertex stores its incident edges and each edge stores its incident vertices.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent source vertices and columns represent destination vertices.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Data on edges and vertices must be stored externally.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Only the cost for one edge can be stored between each pair of vertices.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent the vertices and columns represent the edges.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] The entries indicate the incidence relation between the vertex at a row and edge at a column.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] The following table gives the time complexity cost of performing various operations on graphs, for each of these representations, with |*V*| the number of vertices and |*E*| the number of edges.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] In the matrix representations, the entries encode the cost of following an edge.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] The cost of edges that are not present are assumed to be ∞.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] A representation of adjacent vertices via hash tables leads to an amortized average time complexity of $O(1)$ to test adjacency of two given vertices and to remove an edge and an amortized average time complexity of $O(\deg(x))$ to remove a given vertex x of degree $\deg(x)$ .
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] The time complexity of the other operations and the asymptotic space requirement do not change.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] The parallelization of graph problems faces significant challenges: Data-driven computations, unstructured problems, poor locality and high data access to computation ratio.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] The graph representation used for parallel architectures plays a significant role in facing those challenges.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Poorly chosen representations may unnecessarily drive up the communication cost of the algorithm, which will decrease its scalability.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] In the following, shared and distributed memory architectures are considered.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] In the case of a shared memory model, the graph representations used for parallel processing are the same as in the sequential case, since parallel read-only access to the graph representation (e.g. an adjacency list) is efficient in shared memory.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] In the distributed memory model, the usual approach is to partition the vertex set V of the graph into p sets $V_{0},\dots ,V_{p-1}$ .
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Here, p is the amount of available processing elements (PE).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertex set partitions are then distributed to the PEs with matching index, additionally to the corresponding edges.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Every PE has its own subgraph representation, where edges with an endpoint in another partition require special attention.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] For standard communication interfaces like MPI, the ID of the PE owning the other endpoint has to be identifiable.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] During computation in a distributed graph algorithms, passing information along these edges implies communication.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Partitioning the graph needs to be done carefully - there is a trade-off between low communication and even size partitioning But partitioning a graph is a NP-hard problem, so it is not feasible to calculate them.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Instead, the following heuristics are used.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] 1D partitioning: Every processor gets $n/p$ vertices and the corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be understood as a row-wise or column-wise decomposition of the adjacency matrix.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] For algorithms operating on this representation, this requires an All-to-All communication step as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ message buffer sizes, as each PE potentially has outgoing edges to every other PE.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] 2D partitioning: Every processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Assume the processors are aligned in a rectangle $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ , where $p_{r}$ and $p_{c}$ are the amount of processing elements in each row and column, respectively.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Then each processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix of dimension $(n/p_{r})\times (n/p_{c})$ .
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be visualized as a checkerboard pattern in a matrix.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Therefore, each processing unit can only have outgoing edges to PEs in the same row and column.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] This bounds the amount of communication partners for each PE to $p_{r}+p_{c}-1$ out of $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ possible ones.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Graphs with trillions of edges occur in machine learning, social network analysis, and other areas.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Compressed graph representations have been developed to reduce I/O and memory requirements.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] General techniques such as Huffman coding are applicable, but the adjacency list or adjacency matrix can be processed in specific ways to increase efficiency.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS) are two closely related approaches that are used for exploring all of the nodes in a given connected component.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Both start with an arbitrary node, the "root".
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Strongly connected components can also be found using graph traversals using algorithms such as Kosaraju's algorithm, which is a modified DFS.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] Dijkstra's Algorithm is a Pathfinding Algorithm that can be used on a positively-weighted (meaning all edge weights must be greater than or equal to 0) and/or directed graphs.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be used to find the shortest path between two arbitrarily chosen nodes which is commonly applied in routing problems.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:nebula-graph/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:nebula-graph/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
